				<article> 
					<h2 id="leto">Zvyozdnoe Leto</h2> 
					<p class="post-meta"> 
						Published on November 28, 2023 

						<img class= "img3" src="/public/images/redrosessunnysky.jpeg" alt="Million Red Roses">
					</p> 
					<p> 
						How awesome is the song "Zvyozdnoe Leto" in the video game "Atomic Heart"?!? The game is
						a first person shooter set in an alternate Russia, by game developer Mundfish Studio.
						The songs "Zvyozdnoe Leto" and "Million Red Roses" are by Alla Pugacheva, a musical icon of 
						Soviet Russia; the songs received a remix by Geoffrey Day for use in the game and have enjoyed
						a surge in renewed popularity as a result. And they are currently on repeat on my playlist! 
						Is Atomic Heart a AAA game? No. But I'd give it a solid.....B+. It's so close - but the 
						gameplay isn't as intuitive as it should be and the accents used throughout for the English
						version are jarring. You'd think the main protagonist - a Russian spy and all around Soviet
						special-agent bada55 would speak English in a Russian accent - not an American accent! 
						The NPCs speak a range of regional British accents which is just.....weird! And the stereotype 
						"German Bad Guy" accent	is reminiscent of Colonel Clink from Hogan's Heroes! But those 
						pesky irritations fall away when the beat of Zvyozdnoe Leto rolls in, rogue AI's and 
						mutant plant-zombie abominations start attacking, and you get down to the business
						of blowing them away with the strange and lethal weaponry you've been acquiring and 
						upgrading. Who would've thought a Soviet era song from the late 70s would one day
						provide such an epic a55-kicking beat to blow away the bad guys to?
						<br>

						<a href="#top">Top</a>

					</p> 
